153. ‘Yon enjoy a rotten apple such as the Praetorian soldiers given monkey which they have dressed up to look like a comrade? The ‘agger' seems to be the Servian wall extending from the ‘Porta Collina' to the ‘Porta Esquilina.' Behind this, between the Porta Viminalis and Esquilina, lay the Praetorian camp, and the soldiers amused themselves by dressing up a monkey in a helmet and arming him with a shield and setting him on a goat and teaching him to throw a spear. Some have interpreted the qni tegitur to mean a raw recruit who learns his drill srom a serjeant contemptuously dubbed capella. But the interpretation here given seems the most probable, and the objec- tion which has been taken to it that ab equo iaculari is not Latin, and that ‘ex capella’ would be used instead of ‘a capella‚' is met by the two quotations given by Lewis and others: Prop. iii. 11. 13 ‘Ausa ferox ab equo quondam oppugnare sagittis Maeotis Danaum Penthesilea rates’ and Ovid, A.
